Class Database

  • java.lang.Object
    • Database

  • public class Database
extends java.lang.Object
    This class provides the functionality for storing and accessing the entries for the different restaurants. It uses several different containers to allow access to the restaurant objects by name, city, category, rank, and cost. The class also provides a method to scan in the database from a file and to write the database to a file. Finally, the class allows restricted modifications of the database for adding a review or adding a new entry.
    Author:
    Ivan Evtimov

        public void createDatabaseFromFile(java.lang.String inputFilePath)
                            throws java.lang.IllegalStateException
        This method creates the database from the file. It first scans the file in blocks of code. Then it passes each block of code to the internal containers, each of which has a different ordering.
        Parameters:

        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the input database was wrong

      • search

        public java.util.ArrayList<Restaurant> search(java.lang.String city,
                                     java.lang.String category,
                                     java.lang.String cost,
                                     java.lang.String currDay,
                                     java.lang.String currTime)
        This method is designed to return all restaurants with the given search criteria (only one category allowed!). Please, note that the wildcard (*) can be used on all parameters with the exception of city. For the time, as long as a wildcard is passed either for the day or the time, the search method assumes that both the day and time are irrelevant (since we cannot determine whether the restaurant is open without one of them).
        Parameters:
        city - the city we want to eat in
        category - the category we are looking for
        cost - the cost we are looking for
        currDay - the day and day we want to eat on, written out fully
        currTime - the current time, given in a 24-hour format with leading zero
        Returns:
        an ArrayList with all the restaurants that match this criteria, null if no restaurant matches all of the criteria

      • search

        public java.util.ArrayList<Restaurant> search(java.lang.String city,
                                     java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> categories,
                                     java.lang.String cost,
                                     java.lang.String currDay,
                                     java.lang.String currTime)
        This method is designed to return all restaurants that match the search criteria exactly. If there is more than one category specified in the ArrayList for categories, then the method only returns all restaurants that have all of those categories. If the restauarant is missing one category from the specified list, it will not be returned. If a restaurant has additional categories, however (besides the ones in the array list, it will be returned because it matches the search criteria. Please, note that the wildcard (*) can be used on all parameters with the exception of category. For the time, as long as a wildcard is passed either for the day or the time, the search method assumes that both the day and time are irrelevant (since we cannot determine whether the restaurant is open without one of them).
        Parameters:
        city - the city we want to eat in
        categories - an array list of the categories we are looking for
        cost - the cost we are looking for
        currDay - the day and day we want to eat on, written out fully
        currTime - the current time, given in a 24-hour format with leading zero
        Returns:
        an ArrayList with all the restaurants that match this criteria, null if no restaurant matches all of the criteria

      • searchWithLessMatchingCategories

        public java.util.ArrayList<Restaurant> searchWithLessMatchingCategories(java.lang.String city,
                                                               java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> categoriesArr,
                                                               java.lang.String cost,
                                                               java.lang.String currDay,
                                                               java.lang.String currTime)
        This method provides a more generic search possibility where multiple categories can be entered in an ArrayList. The method returns all restaurants that match at least one of those categories. No wildcard allowed for the categories as they are entered as an arrayList.
        Parameters:
        city - the city we want to eat in
        categoriesArr - the categories we are looking for in an ArrayList
        cost - the cost we are looking for
        currDay - the day and day we want to eat on, written out fully
        currTime - the current time, given in a 24-hour format with leading zero
        Returns:
        an ArrayList with all the restaurants that match this criteria, null if no restaurant matches all of the criteria

      • addNewRestaurant

        public void addNewRestaurant(java.lang.String name,
                    java.lang.String city,
                    java.lang.String category,
                    java.lang.String open,
                    java.lang.String cost)
        This method provides the functionality needed to add a new restaurant to the knowledge base. Since all new restaurants start out with a rank of 0 and no reviewers, it only accepts name, city, category, days when its open, and cost as parameters.
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the new restaurant
        city - the city of the new restaurant
        category - the category/ies of the new restaurant
        open - the opening hours of the new restaurant, as a string
        cost - the cost of the new restaurant ($$$)
